"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">44</A>
Noted for their simple habits.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note45" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref45
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">45</A>
<SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">Titillatio</SPAN> is Cicero's rendering of the Epicurean word <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">γαργαλισμός</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note46" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref46
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">46</A>
Plato, <I>Rep.</I> 329<SPAN CLASS="small">B</SPAN> <SPAN LANG="el" CLASS="Greek">ἀσμενέστατα αὐτὸ ἀπέφυγον ὥσπερ λυττῶντά τινα καὶ ἄγριον δεσπότην ἀποφυγών</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note47" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref47
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">47</A>
<I>Cf.</I> <A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/brut.shtml#59
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Cic. <I>Brutus</I> 58</A>.<!-- 59, actually -->


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note48" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref48
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">48</A>
The real derivation is from <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">occa</SPAN> = <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">rastrum</SPAN>, "a hoe."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note49" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref49
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">49</A>
Xen. <I>Oecon.</I> 4.20.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note50" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref50
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">50</A>
<I>i.e.</I> arranged thus<!--  zzz -->: <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
https://www.hs-augsburg.de/~harsch/Chronologia/Lsante01/Vergilius/ver_ge02.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(EClickHere+'Book 2<BR>of the Georgics'+Lat2+LatSearch+'quadret</SPAN>.')"
onMouseOut="nd();">Virg. <I>Georg.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.277</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note51" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref51
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">51</A>
<I>i.e.</I> instead of being able to refer to the actions of earlier years.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note52" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref52
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">52</A>
Only the columns, praetors, dictators, masters of horse, and provincial governors, while in office, had <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">imperium</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note53" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref53
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">53</A>
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ter.adel.html
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Adelphi</I>, a play of Terence.</A>


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note54" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref54
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">54</A>
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Herodotus/1C*.html#163
	"TARGET="Herodotus_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Herodotus,WIDTH,220)"
onMouseOut="nd();">Herod. <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.163</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note55" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref55
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">55</A>
Literally until (the words) "now applaud" (are spoken). All the plays of Terence and most of those of Plautus close with <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">plaudite</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note56" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref56
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">56</A>
Plato, <I>Phaedo</I> 6; Cic. <I>Somn. Scip.</I> 3<!--</A>SOMNIUM SCIPIONIS (uuu in any of the versions online)-->;
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/cicero/tusc1.shtml#20
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,LatinRef2,WIDTH,195)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Cic. <I>Tusc.</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.20</A>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note57" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref57
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">57</A>
Plutarch
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Lives/Solon+Publicola*.html#1.4
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
in his comparison of Solon and Publicola
	</A>
gives these lines.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note58" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref58
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">58</A>
Or "fate."


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note59" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref59
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">59</A>
<I>Cf.</I> Plato, <I>Phaedo</I> 72<SPAN CLASS="small">E</SPAN>‑73<SPAN CLASS="small">B</SPAN>, 78‑80; <I>Phaedrus</I> 245<SPAN CLASS="small">C</SPAN>.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note60" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref60
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">60</A>
Xenophon, <I>Cyropaedia</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">VIII</SPAN>.7.17‑22.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note61" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref61
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">61</A>
But <I>cf.</I> <A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/de_Divinatione/2*.html#119
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,0,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();"><I>De divinatione</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">II</SPAN>.58.119 ff.</A>, where Cicero refutes and derides this theory.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note62" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref62
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">62</A>
Cicero here confuses Pelias with his half-brother Aeson, whom Medea restored to youth by cutting him up and boiling him in a cauldron.



	<HR CLASS="endnotes"><A ID="endnotes_T"></A>
	<H2>
Thayer's Notes:
	</H2>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Tithonus" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref:Tithonus
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">a</A>
Tithonus was a young man with whom Eos, goddess of the dawn, was enamoured. She asked of Zeus that he be given immortality, but forgot to ask eternal youth for him as well. Ageing past the bounds of a normal human life span, he shrivelled up into a cricket: at least, in the later forms of the myth. The story is first told in the
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Homerica/Hymns/5*.html#218
	"TARGET="Homerica_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Homeric Hymn to Aphrodite</I>, 218‑238</A>. See
	<A HREF="
https://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Apollod.+3.12.4
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Frazer's note to Apollod. <SPAN CLASS="small">III</SPAN>.12.4</A>, and Ovid, who with inimitable charm and circumstance, dots the i's for us
	<A HREF="
http://www.thelatinlibrary.com/ovid/ovid.amor1.shtml
	"TARGET="offsite"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,2,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
(<I>Amores</I>, <SPAN CLASS="small">I</SPAN>.13)</A>.
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
As a speaker, Tithonus, the victim of a ghastly and unnatural old age, could not have been a more bizarre and inappropriate choice; the mere suggestion, followed by the notion that Cicero's intellectual authority might gain or lose depending on his (utterly transparent) choice of a character to pull it off, and finally that hey, Cato picked up more Greek polish than we know — is typical Ciceronian banter; the habits of a pleader at law die hard, and we have a <I>captatio benevolentiae</I>, in which Cicero puts the reader at ease.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="a0 justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:span_to_old_age" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref:span_to_old_age
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">b</A>
This may not be clear to every modern reader. According to the Romans, the ages of a man were five:
	<P CLASS="m3x1 b0 a0 justify">
from birth until he could speak, he was an <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">infans</SPAN>;
	<P CLASS="m3x1 b0 a0 justify">
then, until he assumed the adult toga, usually between 15 and 17, he was a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">puer</SPAN>;
	<P CLASS="m3x1 b0 a0 justify">
after that, up to age 30, he was an <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">adulescens</SPAN> — a person becoming an adult, whence our modern <SPAN CLASS="source">adolescent</SPAN>;
	<P CLASS="m3x1 b0 a0 justify">
between 30 and 45, he was a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">iuvenis</SPAN>, a "young man";
	<P CLASS="m3x1 b0 a0 justify">
after 45, he was a <SPAN LANG="la" CLASS="Latin">senex</SPAN>, an "old man".
	<P CLASS="i1 b0 a0 justify">
Here, Cicero is saying that while for most men 45 years merely represents the span of time from birth all the way to the onset of old age, in Corvinus' case that was only the span of his highest political career: basically a lifetime.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Spartans_give_up_their_seats_to_an_old_man" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref:Spartans_give_up_their_seats_to_an_old_man
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">c</A>
The same story is told by Plutarch,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Plutarch/Moralia/Sayings_of_Spartans*/unknown.html#55
	"TARGET="Plutarch_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Plutarch,WIDTH,PlutarchWidth)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
<I>Apoph. Lac.</I> Ign. 55</A>, but set in Olympia and targeting all non-Spartans, not just the Athenians.


<P CLASS="ivy">❦</P>


	<P CLASS="justify">
	<A CLASS="note" ID="note:Regulus" HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cicero/Cato_Maior_de_Senectute/text*.html#ref:Regulus
"onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,BackRef,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">d</A>
M. Atilius Regulus, a Roman general captured by the Carthaginians, was sent by them to Rome to persuade the Roman senate to make peace — on the condition that he pledge to return to Carthage if they did not. He pledged, went to Rome, and used his energies to persuade the Senate, on the contrary, to continue the war. He then honored his pledge and returned to Carthage, knowing that he would most likely be put to death there, as indeed he was. The story is an often quoted example of Roman rectitude and courage; see
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Cassius_Dio/11*.html#43.26
	"TARGET="Cassius_Dio_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,Dio,WIDTH,190)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Dion Cass. <SPAN CLASS="small">XI</SPAN>.43.26</A>,
	<A HREF="
https://www.livius.org/sources/content/livy/livy-periochae-16-20/#17.1
	"TARGET="Livius"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,toLivius,WIDTH,175)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Livy <I>Periochae</I> <SPAN CLASS="small">XVII</SPAN>.7</A>,
	<A HREF="
E/Roman/Texts/Gellius/7*.html#ref14
	"TARGET="Gellius_E"
onMouseOver="return Ebox(INARRAY,1,WIDTH,165)"
onMouseOut="nd();">
Gellius <SPAN CLASS="small">VII</SPAN>.4</A>.



